Here's the complete migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

Your code contains **three** patterns that break on .NET 8:

| API | Location | Pattern | Why it breaks |
|-----|----------|---------|---------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9); throws `ThreadInterruptedException`, not reliably caught |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Blocking call interruption | Not cancellation-aware; `Interrupt`/`Abort` can't wake it cooperatively |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new();
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        CancellationToken token = _cts.Token;
        try
        {
            while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // WaitAny wakes on EITHER a new event OR cancellation
                WaitHandle.WaitAny([_newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle]);

                if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                    break;

                _newEvent.Reset();

                // Drain all queued items (fixes original race where
                // multiple Enqueue calls could be collapsed into one signal)
                while (true)
                {
                    string? item;
                    lock (_lock)
                    {
                        if (_queue.Count == 0)
                            break;
                        item = _queue.Dequeue();
                    }
                    Handle(item);
                }
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Expected on shutdown — exit cleanly
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // signals the token → wakes WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait for clean exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Original | Migrated | Reason |
|----------|----------|--------|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop cooperatively checks for cancellation |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny([_newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle])` | Wakes on **either** new work or cancellation — no `Interrupt` needed |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Token's WaitHandle becomes signaled, waking `WaitAny` immediately |
| `Thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Cooperative cancellation guarantees the loop exits; no force-kill needed |
| `ManualResetEvent` | `ManualResetEventSlim` | Lighter-weight; avoids OS kernel handle allocation for short waits |
| Single `Dequeue` per signal | Drain loop | Fixes pre-existing race: multiple `Enqueue` calls between signals now all get processed |

## Key Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`WaitOne()` is not token-aware** — You cannot pass a `CancellationToken` to `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()`. You *must* use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with the token's `WaitHandle`, or the thread will never wake on cancellation.

2. **Check cancellation *after* waking** — `WaitAny` doesn't tell you *which* handle fired. Always check `token.IsCancellationRequested` before doing work.

3. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — It's `IDisposable` and leaks timer/callback resources if not disposed. The `IDisposable` pattern on the class ensures cleanup.

4. **No force-kill replacement exists** — If `Join(5000)` times out, there is no .NET 8 equivalent of `Abort`. Design the loop so it *always* exits cooperatively. If `Handle(item)` can hang, pass the token into it too.

5. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — Catch it only at the top-level loop boundary. Let it propagate everywhere else.
